---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { internalHref, siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";

const sdkShape = `kern-<version>-<host-target>/
  bin/
  lib/kern/
  manifest/sdk.json
  toolchain/
    host/
      bin/
      lib/
      include/
      sysroot/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="SDK Layout"
  description="What the Kern SDK archive contains, how release artifacts are split, and why the packaged toolchain layout is explicit."
>
  <section class="doc-shell">
    <div class="section-lead max-w-4xl">
      <div class="eyebrow">SDK Layout</div>
      <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
        SDK layout and artifacts
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        This page describes what the released SDK contains, how it is laid out on disk,
        and how that differs from standalone toolchain artifacts and editor packaging.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Artifacts</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Three release artifacts, three different jobs</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="doc-topic-grid mt-8">
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">SDK archive</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>The normal artifact users install.</li>
          <li>Contains the Kern tools, the shipped library layers, and the packaged host toolchain layout.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">Standalone toolchain archive</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>Mainly for CI, bootstrap, and controlled host-tool validation.</li>
          <li>Not the normal first thing an end user should download.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section>
        <div class="doc-topic-title">VSIX / editor artifact</div>
        <ul class="doc-topic-list">
          <li>The editor integration artifact.</li>
          <li>May bundle a platform-specific `kern-lsp`, but does not replace the SDK itself.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Layout</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Current SDK directory shape</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        The release layout is intentionally moving toward a real SDK shape instead of ad-hoc packaging.
        The current archive already exposes the important structure directly.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,0.8fr)_minmax(0,1.2fr)]">
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{sdkShape}</code></pre>
      <div class="dense-link-list">
        <div class="dense-link-item">
          <div class="dense-link-title">`bin/`</div>
          <p class="dense-link-summary">Host-facing Kern tools: `kernc`, `craft`, and `kern-lsp`.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dense-link-item">
          <div class="dense-link-title">`lib/kern/`</div>
          <p class="dense-link-summary">The official shipped library layers: `base`, `sys`, `rt`, and `std`.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dense-link-item">
          <div class="dense-link-title">`manifest/sdk.json`</div>
          <p class="dense-link-summary">Structured SDK metadata: layout, host target, toolchain resolution, and bundled components.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dense-link-item">
          <div class="dense-link-title">`toolchain/host/`</div>
          <p class="dense-link-summary">The packaged host LLVM/Clang prefix used for release validation and relocatable SDK behavior.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Manifest</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Why `sdk.json` and the bundled toolchain exist</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">`manifest/sdk.json`</h3>
        <ul class="doc-bullet-columns mt-6">
          <li>Records the SDK version and host target.</li>
          <li>Records toolchain resolver order and bundled-first versus system-fallback policy.</li>
          <li>Records the current packaged layout paths under `toolchain/host/`.</li>
          <li>Can also carry per-component checksum and size metadata for packaged toolchain entries.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-2xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Bundled toolchain policy</h3>
        <ul class="doc-bullet-columns mt-6">
          <li>It keeps release quality closer to the environment users actually execute.</li>
          <li>It avoids depending on whatever LLVM happens to be on a CI runner.</li>
          <li>It makes the installed SDK self-describing and relocatable.</li>
          <li>Source-build and ambient `PATH` usage remain lower-priority fallbacks rather than the primary install contract.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Resolution</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Toolchain resolution order</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        When `kernc` needs a host toolchain, the intended installed-SDK behavior stays explicit.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="dense-link-list mt-8">
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">1. `--toolchain-root`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">An explicit user override wins first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">2. SDK-relative bundled toolchain</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">The installed SDK prefers its packaged host toolchain when present.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">3. Explicit environment overrides</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Environment-based control remains available for development and controlled overrides.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="dense-link-item">
        <div class="dense-link-title">4. System `PATH`</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Ambient system toolchains are the final fallback rather than the primary release assumption.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="doc-shell section-divider">
    <div class="section-lead">
      <div class="eyebrow">Next</div>
      <h2 class="mt-4 text-4xl text-[color:var(--kern-ink)]">Related documents</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="dense-link-list mt-8">
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/install")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">Install</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">The normal user-facing path for getting the SDK onto a machine.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={internalHref("/build-from-source")}>
        <div class="dense-link-title">Build from source</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Understand why local developer binaries are a different contract from packaged SDK archives.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/sdk-rebuild-plan.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
        <div class="dense-link-title">SDK rebuild plan</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Repository planning and maintainer detail for the evolving SDK model.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/windows-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
        <div class="dense-link-title">Windows distribution</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Release policy and packaging detail for Windows hosts.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="dense-link-item" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/unix-distribution.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
        <div class="dense-link-title">Unix distribution</div>
        <p class="dense-link-summary">Release policy and archive detail for Unix hosts.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
